\begin_layout Standard
a) What is the threshold gain per unit length?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
At the beginning the light of frequency 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

.
 enters the medium from the left with intensity 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 After passing through the medium of length 
\begin_inset Formula $z=60cm$
\end_inset

 the light has an intensity 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{0}e^{gz}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 is the gain coefficient of the medium.
 After reflecting off the right mirror the intensity drops and is 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{2}I_{0}e^{gz}$
\end_inset

.
 The light then passes through the medium again and the intensity once it
 leaves the medium is now 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{2}I_{0}e^{gz}e^{gz}$
\end_inset

.
 After reflecting off the mirror on the left, the round trip is completed
 and the light now has intensity 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{1}r_{2}I_{0}e^{2gz}$
\end_inset

.
 For what gain 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 do we have that the intensity is unchanged? 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
I_{0} & = & r_{1}r_{2}I_{0}e^{2gz}\\
g & = & -\frac{1}{2z}\ln(r_{1}r_{2})\\
 & = & -\frac{1}{2(0.6m)}\ln(1.0(0.9))=0.0878\text{m}^{-1}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

