\begin_layout Standard
So the light's intensity through each step, using 
\begin_inset Formula $t=1-0.4=0.96$
\end_inset

 as the transmission coefficient through each window surface,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
I_{0}\rightarrow tI_{0}\rightarrow t^{2}I_{0}\rightarrow t^{2}I_{0}e^{gz}\rightarrow t^{3}I_{0}e^{gz}\rightarrow t^{4}I_{0}e^{gz}\rightarrow r_{2}t^{4}I_{0}e^{gz}
\]

\end_inset

Now on the way back
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
r_{2}t^{4}I_{0}e^{gz}\rightarrow r_{2}t^{5}I_{0}e^{gz}\rightarrow r_{2}t^{6}I_{0}e^{gz}\rightarrow r_{2}t^{6}I_{0}e^{gz}e^{gz}\rightarrow r_{2}t^{8}I_{0}e^{2gz}\rightarrow r_{1}r_{2}t^{8}I_{0}e^{2gz}
\]

\end_inset

So we want 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
I_{0} & = & r_{1}r_{2}t^{8}I_{0}e^{2gz}\\
r_{1}r_{2}t^{8}e^{2gz} & = & 1\\
2gz & = & -\ln(r_{1}r_{2}t^{8})\\
g & = & -\frac{1}{2z}\ln(r_{1}r_{2}t^{8})\\
 & = & -\frac{1}{2(0.6m)}\ln(1.0(0.9)(0.96)^{8})\\
 & = & 0.36\text{m}^{-1}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

What this means is that to get a laser to work with these silly windows
 in the way, we would need a medium whose threshold gain needs to be much
 higher so the light does not lose intensity.
